The full-blown crisis in Lebanon
Beirut — — Looking back, financial crises often seemed to have precursors; but they rarely pointed clearly to the course of history.
The situation in Lebanon is similarly fraught with a foreseeable crisis that has plunged the country into high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's long internal war (1975-1990), its economy and political system have been supported by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a sustained rise in public debt.
At a certain point, external capital inflows had to cease. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This sudden halt in capital flows brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit amounts to 25% of its gross domestic product, with its meager export base unable to cover the cost of necessary imports.
The second issue is fiscal matters.
Lebanon's public debt now totals over 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the weight of the economic recession, with a budget deficit already sizable at 10% of GDP in 2019 and continuing to rapidly expand.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Major banks, which are the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have made substantial investments in Lebanese sovereign debt (accounting for an average of 50% of their portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises together have plunged Lebanon's economy into a abyss.
Companies desperate for loans and imports have begun laying off workers or shutting down entirely.
Economic downturns could lead to a Lebanese Great Depression.
The primary source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil, but rather expatriates who invest at high interest rates and under the fixed exchange rate tied to the US dollar.
So it is no surprise that signs of "Dutch disease" abound: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the saving rate to an implausibly low level – 3% of GDP.
Inequality is high and rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, significantly weakening the competitiveness of tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated youth.
But most importantly, large capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites extracted wealth from both public and private sectors, establishing a bloated clique in power.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, with broader macroeconomic challenges remaining entirely unresolved.
Financial crises sparked a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets to oppose sectarianism and demand an end to corruption.
Despite this, so far, the government's response to Lebanon's economic problems has overwhelmingly favored the elites, indicating that this crisis might ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing each bank's major shareholders, including ruling politicians, to decide how much cash could be withdrawn quantitatively.
Actually, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
Moreover, the central bank lowered deposit rates but has not reduced public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its main foreign debts owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling state assets at fire-sale prices to elite-affiliated entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, while elites allowed access to low-exchange-rate US dollars, whereas ordinary citizens faced a rapidly depreciating market exchange rate, currently discounted by 40%.
When the country began printing Lebanese pounds to pay civil servant salaries, the devaluation would accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already started paying interest on dollar deposits in Lebanese pounds (dollar deposits account for over 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to erode public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction was shifted to depositors through "lebanization," the banks' equity was largely spared.
If this were to happen, Lebanon's middle class would significantly shrink due to lower real wages and pensions, and the depletion of savings.
The emigration of educated youth will accelerate, and even the economic interests of immigrant communities — upon which this system depends — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poverty-stricken population, one that can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
Finally, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
The establishment of the new republic by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe it falls far short of its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, cronyism, and inequality.
They hope to establish vibrant high-tech industries, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create greater synergies with diaspora communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, secured by bank equity, and to force a 1% of deposit holders who account for more than 50% of total deposits to reduce their deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and a comprehensive improvement in the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the eradication of corrupt behavior and increased spending on social projects and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
Now the infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of larger struggles as the country seeks new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a致命 threat to the country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
